---
import "../styles/global.css";

interface Props {
  title: string;
}

const { title } = Astro.props;
---

<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
    <title>{title}</title>
  </head>
  <body class="min-h-screen bg-zinc-950 text-zinc-100">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-4 py-12">
      <header class="mb-8">
        <div>
          <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold">@klinking/squircle</h1>
          <div class="mt-1 flex gap-3">
            <a
              href="https://github.com/dogmar/squircle"
              class="inline-block text-sm text-indigo-400 hover:underline"
              >GitHub</a
            >
            <a
              href="/demos"
              class="inline-block text-sm text-indigo-400 hover:underline"
              >Demos</a
            >
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="mt-2 text-zinc-400">
          We all love the squircle! It's great, we can use it to make corners
          feel <i>extra</i> smooth. Gives that little bit of zhuzh. Others can tell
          you all about the math and why we love it. And now we can use them in CSS!
          There's just one problem... for the same border-radius, the squircle will
          look less rounded than the circle. That's where this package comes in.
        </p>
      </header>
    </div>

    <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-4 pt-8">
      <slot />

      <footer
        class="flex gap-4 border-t border-zinc-800 pt-6 text-xs text-zinc-600"
      >
        <a
          href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/@klinking/squircle"
          class="hover:text-zinc-400">npm</a
        >
        <a
          href="https://github.com/dogmar/squircle"
          class="hover:text-zinc-400">GitHub</a
        >
        <a
          href="https://caniuse.com/?search=corner-shape"
          class="hover:text-zinc-400">Browser Support</a
        >
      </footer>
    </div>
  </body>
</html>
